# 💰 Managing Session Costs

Session length is the primary cost driver when running Claude agents. Understanding how costs compound — and how to control them — is the difference between a $15/month setup and a $150/week surprise.

---

## How costs accumulate

Every model turn sends the full conversation history as context. As a session grows, each turn costs more than the last because you're paying for all previous turns again.

A session with 100 turns is not 100x the cost of 1 turn — it's more like 5,000x, because turn 100 sends all 99 previous turns as context.

**Real example:**
A single Heidi session running continuously for 6 days accumulated:
- 616 model turns
- 1,846 messages
- $153 in costs

The same workload with daily resets: $5–15/session.

---

## The Frank Pattern — Nightly Reset

The most effective cost control is a nightly session reset. Here's how it works:

1. **Frank runs at 3 AM** (ops agent, scheduled via cron or automation)
2. **Reads the primary agent's workspace** — MEMORY.md, today's daily notes, SYSTEMS.md
3. **Distills to essential context** — 500–1,000 tokens covering what the agent needs to resume
4. **Starts a fresh session** with that distilled context injected as the system prompt
5. **Old session ends** — context resets, costs reset

The key insight: **the transcript is not your memory. The files are.**

Your agent does not lose continuity when the session resets. It loses dead weight.

---

## What to inject at session start

Not everything needs to come back. A lean startup context includes:

**Always inject:**
- AGENTS.md (security rules and hierarchy)
- SOUL.md (identity and values)
- USER.md (who they are serving)
- MEMORY.md summary (recent events, ongoing situations)
- TOOLS.md (resource IDs and endpoints)

**Inject if relevant today:**
- Today's date and day of week
- Upcoming events in the next 48 hours
- Any open action items from yesterday

**Do not inject:**
- Full conversation transcripts
- Old daily notes beyond the last 2–3 days
- Resolved situations

---

## Cost benchmarks

| Session pattern | Est. daily cost | Est. monthly cost |
|----------------|----------------|-------------------|
| Daily reset, moderate use | $0.50–1.50 | $15–45 |
| Every 3–4 day reset | $2–5 per session | $20–50 |
| No reset, continuous | $10–25/day | $300–750 |

These are estimates based on Claude Sonnet pricing. Costs vary by model and usage patterns.

---

## Setting up a nightly reset

The simplest implementation uses a cron job or automation platform (Make.com, Zapier, n8n) to:

1. Trigger at a set time (3 AM works well — quiet period, ready for morning)
2. Read the workspace files you want to inject
3. Start a new Claude API session with those files as the system prompt
4. Send a startup message ("Good morning, Heidi. Please read your workspace and confirm you are ready.")
5. Log the session ID for monitoring

If you are using Claude Code, you can script this directly. If you are using claude.ai, you will need to do this manually — paste the startup context at the beginning of each new conversation.

---

## Signs your sessions need better management

- Your morning brief is slow to generate
- The agent seems confused about recent events
- Your API costs are climbing week over week
- The agent references things from days ago as if they just happened

All of these are symptoms of sessions that have grown too long.

---

## Manual reset (no Frank agent)

If you are not running an ops agent yet, you can reset manually:

1. At the end of each day, ask your agent: "Please update MEMORY.md with today's key events and any open items."
2. Start a new session the next morning
3. Paste your core files (AGENTS.md, SOUL.md, USER.md, MEMORY.md, TOOLS.md) as the opening context
4. Continue

This is more work but achieves the same result. Once you are comfortable with the system, automating it with a Frank-style agent is worth the setup time.
